{"cursor":"2618","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox political party\n| name_english = Historical Right name_native = Destra Storica logo = leader =\n| Camillo Benso di Cavour, Bettino Ricasoli, Marco Minghetti, Antonio\n| Starabba di RudinÃ¬, Sidney Sonnino leader1_title = leader1_name =\n| leader2_title = leader2_name = leader3_title = leader3_name = leader4_title =\n| leader4_name = foundation = 1849 dissolution = 1921 headquarters = newspaper =\n| membership_year= membership = ideology = Conservatism, Liberal\n| conservatism, Economic liberalism, Laissez faire, Liberalism, Right-\n| libertarianism, Classical liberalism, Unionism, Italian nationalism\n| position = Centre-right, to Right-wing coalition = international = european\n| = europarl = website = colorcode = country = Italy\n}}\n\nThe 'Historical Right' (Destra Storica), originally known as 'Right' (Destra),\nwas a Classical Liberal, Conservative and nationalist political party in Italy.\nIt was founded in 1849 under the government of Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour;\nwith the Historical Left it was one of the two biggest parties in Italy during\nthe 19th and early 20th century.\n\nThe Historical Right, known as the heir of Cavour and the expression of the\nliberal bourgeoisie, won the Italian general election of 1865. Its members were\nmostly large landowners, industrialists and people related to the military.\n\nThe Right dominated the political life in Italy until 1876, when the right-wing\ngovernment of Marco Minghetti collapsed; it returned to the government at times\nafterward. In 1921 the old parties were dissolved, giving way to new alignments\nsuch as the Socialist Party, the Communist Party, the People's Party and the\nFascist Party.\n","linknr":255,"url":"Historical_Right","recorded":1375082343,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Historical_Right&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Historical_Right&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.ph